Saul of corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my place, drunk.
So I suggested he not drive.
He asked me why.
« You have drunk, » I said to him, « aren't you afraid of the police? »
Boris replied to me: "No, I have a document with Benjamin Franklin's image on it, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with a $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police take bribes, but I worried that Boris would meet a policeman who was not corrupt.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to enter the traffic police force, you have to buy your chief's silence.
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your chief's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things the right way drown in bureaucratic hassles.
By paying 100 dollars, you can drive around town without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels seen today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or an abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers and even the Kremlin: no one anywhere is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of Moscow's most beautiful suburbs.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and tastelessly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and heard in response that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another to the son of Moscow's prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax office official.
Corruption now represents a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it had not been conducted by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
The Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that transported the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims perished during the assault intended to free the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A precaution quite pointless.
Today, no one controls the buses anymore.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along his route, and always for the same reason.
A policeman came to ask him: "do you know what the price is?", and the driver replied: "of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without the bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at every stop, that is, entire days for the journey.
The war against Chechnya continues endlessly not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaida and all the "international terrorist" network but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, maps indicating where the minefields are, and provide the rebels with forged documents.
In May of this year, during the explosions in Kaspiisk, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide there are no gunsmith shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers who fight the rebels have, on the contrary, ammunition stocks, from where the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only the weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, and yet no fight has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more harshly?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more you will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to combat corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those called "simple people" view this phenomenon with goodwill.
They say about their mayor "of course he's corrupt, but look at all he has done for the city!"
Ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller had stopped her by telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on board the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will remove your son's name from the list or else bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption of Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened.
Removing corruption could well leave the State without citizens, but if the progression of corruption is not stopped, the citizens will soon be left without a State.
